{"title_page": "Deportivo Alav\u00e9s", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname      = Deportivo Alav\u00e9s\n| image         = Deportivo Alaves logo.svg\n| image_size    = 300\n| fullname      = Deportivo Alav\u00e9s, S.A.D.\n| nickname      = ''Babazorros''<br />''El Glorioso'' (The glorious one)\n| founded       = {{Start date and age|1921|1|23|df=y}} as ''Sport Friends Club''\n| ground        = [[Mendizorrotza Stadium|Mendizorrotza]]\n| capacity      = 19,840 <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/289723/premier-league-v-laliga-stadiums-all-40-clubs-ranked-capacity-2017-18-season-170927256259/|title=Premier League v LaLiga stadiums: All 40 clubs ranked by current capacity|last=|first=|date=2017-09-27|website=talkSPORT|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n| owner         = [[Saski Baskonia]]\n| chrtitle      = President\n| chairman      = Alfonso Fern\u00e1ndez de Troc\u00f3niz\n| mgrtitle      = Head coach\n| manager       = [[Asier Garitano]]\n| league        = [[La Liga]]\n| season        = [[2018\u201319 La Liga|2018\u201319]]\n| position      = La Liga, 11th\n| website       = http://www.alaves.com\n| pattern_la1   = _alaves1920h\n| pattern_b1    = _alaves1920h\n| pattern_ra1   = _alaves1920h\n| pattern_sh1   = _alaves1920h\n| pattern_so1   = _alaves1920h\n| leftarm1      = 0A3FF5\n| body1         = 0A3FF5\n| rightarm1     = 0A3FF5\n| shorts1       = 0A3FF5\n| socks1        = 0A3FF5\n| pattern_la2   = _alaves1920a\n| pattern_b2    = _alaves1920a\n| pattern_ra2   = _alaves1920a\n| pattern_sh2   = _alaves1920a\n| pattern_so2   = _alaves1920a\n| leftarm2      = FFFFFF\n| body2         = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2     = FFFFFF\n| shorts2       = FFFFFF\n| socks2        = FF0000\n| pattern_la3   = _alaves1920t\n| pattern_b3    = _alaves1920t\n| pattern_ra3   = _alaves1920t\n| pattern_sh3   = _alaves1920t\n| pattern_so3   = _alaves1920t\n| leftarm3      = FFFFFF\n| body3         = FFFFFF\n| rightarm3     = FFFFFF\n| shorts3       = FFFFFF\n| socks3        = FFFFFF\n| current       = 2019\u201320 Deportivo Alav\u00e9s season\n}}\n'''Deportivo Alav\u00e9s, S.A.D.''' ({{IPA-es|depo\u027e\u02c8ti\u03b2o ala\u02c8\u03b2es}}; ''Sporting Alav\u00e9s''), usually abbreviated to '''Alav\u00e9s''', is a [[List of football clubs in Spain|Spanish football club]] based in [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]], [[\u00c1lava]], in the [[Autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] of the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque Country]]. Founded on 23 January 1921 as '''Sport Friends Club''', it plays in the highest football category of [[Liga de F\u00fatbol Profesional|The Liga Nacional de F\u00fatbol Profesional]], [[La Liga]], since [[2016\u201317 Deportivo Alav\u00e9s season|the 2016\u201317 season]].\n\nIt is recognized as the least successful team in the Basque Country following [[Athletic Bilbao|Athletic Club]] of [[Bilbao]] and [[Real Sociedad|Real Sociedad de Futbol]] of [[San Sebasti\u00e1n]]. Its biggest success was in 2001 when, in the year of its debut in European competition, it was one of the finalists in the [[2001 UEFA Cup Final]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], being defeated 5\u20134 by [[golden goal#Association football|golden goal]]. In 2017, the club reached the final of the [[2017 Copa del Rey Final|Copa del Rey]], losing out 3\u20131 to [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/may/27/barcelona-alaves-copa-del-rey-final|title=Lionel Messi inspires Barcelona to Copa del Rey final triumph against William Yu Lin|first=Press|last=Association|date=27 May 2017|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n\nThe team's home kit is blue and white-striped shirt, blue shorts and white socks. It holds home matches at the 19,840-seater [[Mendizorrotza Stadium]]<ref name=\":1\" /> and uses other facilities located in [[Ciudad Deportiva Jos\u00e9 Luis Compa\u00f1\u00f3n|Ibaia]] dedicated to training.\n\n==History==\nFounded in 1921 the initial name of the club was Sport Friends, but on 23 January 1921 the name was changed to the current one.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deportivoalaves.com/club/hitos-historicos|title=La historia del Club {{!}} Alav\u00e9s \u2013 Web Oficial|website=La historia del Club {{!}} Alav\u00e9s \u2013 Web Oficial|language=es|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> Alav\u00e9s was the first club to win promotion from the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] to [[La Liga]] in [[1929\u201330 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1929\u201330]], a stint which would last three years. In its first season in Primera Divisi\u00f3n Alav\u00e9s finished 8th from 10 teams, just 1 point away from being relegated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.resultados-futbol.com/primera1931|title=Primera Divisi\u00f3n, Temporada 1930/1931 \u2013 laliga, liga santander, la liga santander, campeonato nacional de liga de primera divisi\u00f3n, liga espa\u00f1ola|website=www.resultados-futbol.com|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>  \n\nIn [[1953\u201354 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1953\u201354]] the club would reach the top league again for a two-year spell. With Roman Galarraga as a coach, the club reached long-awaited promotion to Segunda Divisi\u00f3n in the 1973\u201374 season.<ref name=\":0\" /> In June 1983, after having avoided the relegation in the previous season, Alav\u00e9s went down to Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B, where remained until the [[1985\u201386 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1985\u201386]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alaves.elcorreo.com/historia/|title=Historia del Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|website=Alaves  \u2013 El Correo|language=es|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> After years of seriously facing disappearance which lasted well into the 1990s (playing in the [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|fourth tier]] during the late 1980s), Alav\u00e9s finally achieved a promotion back into the Segunda Divisi\u00f3n in [[1994\u201395 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1994\u201395]] after two consecutive years of winning their group in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] \u2013 created as the new third level in 1977 \u2013 but failing in the promotion play-offs.\n\nAfter winning the Segunda Divisi\u00f3n in [[1997\u201398 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1997\u201398]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lafutbolteca.com/deportivo-alaves-s-a-d/|title=Deportivo Alav\u00e9s, S.A.D. :: La Futbolteca. Enciclopedia del F\u00fatbol Espa\u00f1ol|language=ES-es|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Alav\u00e9s returned to the top level after a 42-year [[Wikt:hiatus|hiatus]]. Following their [[1998\u201399 La Liga|return season]] in which they escaped relegation by a single point, they achieved two wins against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in [[1999\u20132000 La Liga|the following campaign]] and would qualify for the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] for the first time upon finishing sixth (to date, their highest-ever placing, coming just 12 years after their lowest-ever: eighth in their group in the [[1987\u201388 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|fourth level]]).\n\n[[File:Liverpool vs Alaves 2001-05-16.svg|thumb|Lineups of the [[2001 UEFA Cup Final]] between [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and Alav\u00e9s.]]\nAs well as concluding the domestic campaign in tenth position, in [[2000\u201301 La Liga|2000\u201301]] the Basque club reached the final of the [[2000\u201301 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] after beating [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://elpais.com/diario/2001/02/23/deportes/982882801_850215.html|title=El Alav\u00e9s incendia San Siro|trans-title=Alav\u00e9s set fire to San Siro|publisher=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|language=es|date=23 February 2001|accessdate=24 February 2019 }}</ref> [[Rayo Vallecano]] and [[1. FC Kaiserslautern]], the latter in a crushing 9\u20132 aggregate victory.<ref name=heck>{{cite web|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/what-heck-happened-alaves-after-2001|title=What the heck happened to Alaves after 2001?|work=[[FourFourTwo]] |author=Robert O'Connor|date=18 May 2016|accessdate=24 February 2019 }}</ref> The final ended in a [[2001 UEFA Cup Final|4\u20135 loss]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], Alav\u00e9s losing to an \"own-[[golden goal]]\" after taking the match to extra time. The match also featured two red cards and two disallowed goals in extra time in addition to the nine goals which did count, and has been described by some observers as one of the greatest showpiece games in the competition's history.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2317064/The-greatest-matches-of-all-time.html The greatest matches of all time]; [[The Daily Telegraph]], 4 July 2007</ref>\n\nAlav\u00e9s ended [[2001\u201302 La Liga|2001\u201302]] in seventh position and qualified for the UEFA Cup for a second time, although the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|European campaign of 2002\u201303]] was far less successful than two years earlier, with an opening win over [[MKE Ankarag\u00fcc\u00fc|Ankarag\u00fcc\u00fc]] followed by a defeat to another Turkish [[S\u00fcper Lig]] side, [[Be\u015fikta\u015f J.K.|Be\u015fikta\u015f]]. On 26 January 2003, the club celebrated their 100th win in La Liga after defeating [[Real Valladolid]] 3\u20131.\n\nAlthough Alav\u00e9s were [[relegation|relegated]] after [[2002\u201303 La Liga|2002\u201303]], they regained top flight status two years later.<ref name=heck/> In this time, Alav\u00e9s was bought by Ukrainian\u2013American businessman [[Dmitry Pietrman]], and several clashes followed with the club's coaches, players<ref>[http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/178817/0/futbol/alaves/peterman/ Carreras denuncia el \"trato vejatorio\" de Piterman (Carreras denounces \"vexatious treatment\" by Piterman)]; 20 Minutos, 16 February 2006 {{in lang|es}}</ref> and fans alike.<ref>[http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/93279/0/piterman/aficionados/subnormales/ Dimitri Piterman llama \"subnormales\" a los aficionados del Alav\u00e9s (Dimitri Piterman calls Alav\u00e9s' fans \"morons\")]; 20 Minutos, 22 February 2006 {{in lang|es}}</ref> The top-division return only lasted [[2005\u201306 La Liga|one season]] as the club went through three head coaches and finished in 18th position, one point from safety. Piterman departed in 2007, leaving the club deep in debt after his tenure. After two years of battling against relegation to the third level, Alav\u00e9s eventually succumbed in [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2008\u201309]].\n\nA subsequent black period in ''Segunda B'' lasted four years until Alav\u00e9s was bought by [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Querejeta]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://alaves.elcorreo.com/noticias/2013-07-29/querejeta-hace-acciones-alaves-201307292006.html|title=Querejeta compra las acciones del Alav\u00e9s que ten\u00eda la familia Ortiz de Z\u00e1rate|trans-title=Querejeta bought Alav\u00e9s' shares that the Ortiz de Z\u00e1rate family held|publisher=[[El Correo]]|date=29 July 2013|accessdate=26 February 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref> and [[2012\u201313 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|were promoted again]] to the second division in 2013 as [[2013 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs#Final|overall champions of the third tier]], providing an opportunity to sort out its economic difficulties. Three years later, on 29 May 2016, Alav\u00e9s was promoted to La Liga as [[2015\u201316 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second tier champions]] after beating [[CD Numancia|Numancia]] 2\u20130 to overtake [[CD Legan\u00e9s|Legan\u00e9s]] on the final day.\n[[File:Deporalaves2.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]] vs. Alav\u00e9s.]]\n\nOn 10 September 2016, Alav\u00e9s got their first win of [[2016\u201317 La Liga|their return season in La Liga]] by defeating defending La Liga champions Barcelona 2\u20131 at the [[Camp Nou]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2016_17/la-liga/jornada_3/bar_ala/|title=Glorioso Matagigantes|trans-title=Glorious Giantkillers|publisher=Marca|language=Spanish|date=10 September 2016|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref>  On 7 February 2017, Alav\u00e9s qualified for the [[2017 Copa del Rey Final]] after eliminating [[Celta de Vigo]] in the semi-finals of [[2016\u201317 Copa del Rey|the competition]]. This was the first time in their history that the club had qualified for the final of the national cup, their previous best being the semi-finals in [[1997\u201398 Copa del Rey#Semi-Finals|1998]] and [[2003\u201304 Copa del Rey#Semifinals|2004]]. Their opponents in the final would be Barcelona, and coincidentally the two clubs met in the league directly after their cup semi-finals; the [[Catalonia|Catalans]] inflicted a 6\u20130 defeat on Alav\u00e9s in their own Mendizorrotza Stadium, exacting revenge for the result earlier in the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38880698|title=Alav\u00e9s 0\u20136 Barcelona, February 2017|publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref> Barcelona also won the final, held at the [[Estadio Vicente Calder\u00f3n]] with a 3\u20131 scoreline,<ref name=BBC>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39909498|title=Barcelona 3\u20131 Alav\u00e9s|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 May 2017|accessdate=21 September 2017}}</ref> meaning there would be no return to European competition for Alav\u00e9s. In the La Liga that season Alav\u00e9s finished 9th with 14 wins, 13 draws and 11 losses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.resultados-futbol.com/primera2017|title=Primera Divisi\u00f3n, Temporada 2016/2017 \u2013 laliga, liga santander, la liga santander, campeonato nacional de liga de primera divisi\u00f3n, liga espa\u00f1ola|website=www.resultados-futbol.com|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Seasons==\n\n===Season to season===\n{|\n|valign=\"top\" width=0%|\n{|  class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#f0f6fa;\"\n!Season\n!Tier\n!Division\n!Place\n![[Copa del Rey]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:silver;\"|[[1929 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1929]]\n|style=\"background:silver;\"|2\n|style=\"background:silver;\"|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2\u00aa]]\n|style=\"background:silver;\"|3rd\n!style=\"