ay-offs]]}} [[2012\u201313 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B#Group 2|2012\u201313]]{{efn|Promoted in [[2013 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs#Group Winners Promotion Play-off|play-offs]], overall champion of division}}\n\n*'''[[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]]'''\n: '''Winners (5)''':{{efn|[[Spanish football league system#Evolution of the Spanish league system|Third tier]]}}  [[1940\u201341 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Group A2|1940\u201341]],{{efn|Promoted in [[1940\u201341 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Group A|play-offs]]}} [[1960\u201361 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Group IV|1960\u201361]],{{efn|Promoted in [[1960\u201361 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Promotion playoff|play-offs]]}} [[1964\u201365 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Group IV|1964\u201365]],{{efn|Not promoted in [[1964\u201365 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Promotion playoff|play-offs]]}} [[1967\u201368 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Group 4|1967\u201368]],{{efn|Promoted in [[1967\u201368 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Promotion to Segunda Divisi\u00f3n (champions)|play-offs]]}} [[1973\u201374 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Group II|1973\u201374]]{{efn|Promoted directly}}\n: '''Winners''':{{efn|[[Spanish football league system#Evolution of the Spanish league system|Fourth tier]]}} [[1989\u201390 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n#Group 4|1989\u201390]]{{efn|Promoted directly}}\n\n*'''Regional Championship<ref name=rsssf>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/span-nortechamp.html|title=Spain - List of Champions of Norte|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|date=21 January 2000|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref>'''\n:[[Biscay Championship]]: 1929\u201330\n:[[:es:Campeonato Regional de Guip\u00fazcoa|Gipuzkoa Championship]]: 1938\u201339\n\n*'''[[Copa Federaci\u00f3n de Espa\u00f1a]]'''\n: '''Winners:''': [[1945\u201346 Copa Federaci\u00f3n de Espa\u00f1a|1945\u201346]]\n\n*'''[[Copa del Rey]]'''\n: ''Runners-up'': [[2016\u201317 Copa del Rey|2016\u201317]]\n\n===European competitions===\n*'''[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]'''\n: ''Runners-up:'' [[2000\u201301 UEFA Cup|2000\u201301]]\n\n====Notes====\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Stadium information==\n[[File:Mendizorrotza.jpg|280px|thumb|Mendizorrotza stadium]]\n*'''Name''' \u2013 [[Estadio Mendizorrotza|Mendizorrotza]]\n*'''City''' \u2013 [[Vitoria-Gasteiz]]\n*'''Capacity''' \u2013 19,840<ref>[http://www.alaves.com/instalaciones/ Mendizorrotza Stadium] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131127110951/http://www.alaves.com/instalaciones/ |date=27 November 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://depor.com/futbol-internacional/espana/real-madrid-vs-deportivo-alaves-en-vivo-laliga-santander-fecha-horarios-y-canales-de-tv-estadio-de-mendizorroza-espn-movistar-laliga-benzema-zidane-alineaciones-estadisticas-futbol-en-directo-gratis-online-espana-es-nnda-nnrt-noticia/|title=\u00a1Gr\u00edtalo merengue! Real Madrid gan\u00f3 2-1 al Alav\u00e9s por LaLiga Santander|last=Depor|first=Redacci\u00f3n|date=2019-11-30|website=Depor|language=es|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n*'''Inauguration''' \u2013 1924\n*'''Pitch size''' \u2013 105&nbsp;m x 67&nbsp;m\n*'''Other facilities''' \u2013 ''[[Beto\u00f1o Sports Complex|El Glorioso]]'' and ''[[Ciudad Deportiva Jos\u00e9 Luis Compa\u00f1\u00f3n|Jos\u00e9 Luis Compa\u00f1\u00f3n]]''\n\n==Famous players==\n{{see also|Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s players}}\n*{{flagicon|Norway}} [[Dan Eggen]] (1999\u20132003)\n\n==Coaches==\n{{see also|Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s managers}}\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Amadeo Garc\u00eda]] (1926\u201327)\n*{{flagicon|England}} [[Walter Harris (football manager)|Walter Harris]] (1928)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Ram\u00f3n Encinas]] (1931\u201332)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Amadeo Garc\u00eda]] (1932\u201339)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Baltasar Alb\u00e9niz]] (1939)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Francisco Gamborena]] (1940\u201341)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Baltasar Alb\u00e9niz]] (1947\u201348)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Manuel Echezarreta]] (1954\u201356)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Rafael Iriondo]] (1958\u201359)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Manuel Echezarreta]] (1959\u201360)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Ignacio Izaguirre Terreros|Ignacio Izagirre]] (1968\u201369) (coach)\n*{{flagicon|Hungary}}{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Ferenc Pusk\u00e1s]] (1968\u201369) {{small|(technical director)}}\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Garc\u00eda de Andoin|Garc\u00eda de Andoin]] (1972)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Koldo Aguirre]] (1972\u201373)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Ignacio Eizaguirre]] (1975)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Iglesias Fern\u00e1ndez|Jose\u00edto]] (1976\u201378)\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jes\u00fas Aranguren]] (1978\u201380)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Garc\u00eda de Andoin|Garc\u00eda de Andoin]] (1980\u201382)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Esnal|Man\u00e9]] (1984\u201385)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Nando Yosu]] (1985\u201386)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Luis Costa (Spanish footballer)|Luis Costa]] (1992\u201393)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio Irulegui]] (1993\u201394)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jes\u00fas Aranguren]] (1994\u201397)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Esnal|Man\u00e9]] (1997\u201303)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jes\u00fas Aranguren]] (2003)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Pepe Mel]] (2003\u201304)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Juan Carlos Oliva]] (2006)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Julio Ba\u00f1uelos]] (2006)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Fabriciano Gonz\u00e1lez|Fabri]] (2007)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Josu Uribe]] (2007\u201308)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Julio Ba\u00f1uelos]] (2008)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Salmer\u00f3n]] (2008)\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Manix Mandiola]] (2008\u201309)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Francisco Javier L\u00f3pez Castro|Javi L\u00f3pez]] (2009)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Luis de la Fuente Castillo|Luis de la Fuente]] (2011)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Carlos Granero]] (2011\u201312)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Natxo Gonz\u00e1lez]] (2012\u201313)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Juan Carlos Mandi\u00e1]] (2013\u201314)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Alberto L\u00f3pez Fern\u00e1ndez|Alberto L\u00f3pez]] (2014\u201315)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Jos\u00e9 Bordal\u00e1s]] (2015\u201316)\n*{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Mauricio Pellegrino]] (2016\u201317)\n*{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Luis Zubeld\u00eda]] (2017)\n*{{flagicon|Italy}}{{flagicon|Albania}} [[Gianni De Biasi]] (2017)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Abelardo Fern\u00e1ndez|Abelardo]] (2017\u201319)\n*{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Asier Garitano]] (2019\u2013)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Affiliated clubs==\n===Alav\u00e9s B/C===\n{{main|Deportivo Alav\u00e9s B}}\nThe club's primary reserve team is [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s B]], founded in 1960 and currently playing at the amateur [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]] level of the senior Spanish system. When that team gained promotion to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] in 2000, a further reserve side [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s C]] was formed, later partnering with local team [[Club San Ignacio]], but the C-team was discontinued in 2005 due to the poor financial situation at the club. San Ignacio and most other teams in the vicinity of Vitoria-Gasteiz continue to operate as partner clubs of Alav\u00e9s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deportivoalaves.com/futbol-base/clubes-convenidos|title=Clubes Convenidos|trans-title=Partner Clubs|language=Spanish|publisher=Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|date=1 August 2017|accessdate=24 January 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clubsanignacio.com/el-c-d-san-ignacio/el-club-y-el-alaves/|title=CD San Ignacio y CF Adurtzabal renuevan hasta 2020 su convenio con el Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|trans-title=CD San Ignacio and CF Adurtzabal renew their agreement with Deportivo Alav\u00e9s until 2020|language=Spanish|publisher=C.D. San Ignacio|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=24 January 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/05/25/segunda/1527249565_070373.html|title=El Alav\u00e9s completa una gran estructura deportiva con el ascenso del San Ignacio a Tercera |trans-title=The Alav\u00e9s completes a extensive sports structure with the rise of San Ignacio to Tercera|language=es |work=[[Diario AS]]|author=Javier Lekuona|date=25 May 2018|accessdate=24 January 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.noticiasdealava.eus/2018/07/18/alaves/el-alaves-cede-ibaia-al-san-ignacio-para-su-temporada-en-tercera|title=El Alav\u00e9s cede Ibaia al San Ignacio para su temporada en tercera |trans-title=Alav\u00e9s gives Ibaia to San Ignacio for their season in Tercera|language=es |work=Noticias de \u00c1lava|author1=Asier P\u00e9rez|author2=Jorge Mu\u00f1oz |date=18 July 2018|accessdate=24 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===California Victory===\nIn 2007, Alav\u00e9s operated a team in the [[USL First Division]] in the United States called the [[California Victory]]. The team played at [[Kezar Stadium]] in San Francisco, California, and wore the Alav\u00e9s colors. However, Alav\u00e9s, under new ownership, pulled its support for the club later that year, after which the Victory folded.\n\n===NK Rude\u0161===\nIn May 2017, Alav\u00e9s signed a ten-year partnership deal with [[NK Rude\u0161]], freshly promoted [[Croatian First Football League]] club, with Rude\u0161 acting as a feeder club to Alav\u00e9s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportnet.rtl.hr/vijesti/503431/nogomet-2-hnl/deportivo-alaves-i-nk-rudes-predstavili-desetogodisnju-suradnju/|title=Deportivo Alaves i NK Rude\u0161 predstavili desetogodi\u0161nju suradnju|trans-title=Deportivo Alaves and NK Rude\u0161 presented future ten-year cooperation|publisher=[[Sportnet.hr]]|date=12 May 2017|accessdate=11 June 2017|language=Croatian}}</ref>\nIn June 2018, Deportivo Alav\u00e9s and NK Rude\u0161 ended its partnership agreement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nkrudes.com/en/deportivo-alaves-and-nk-rudes-ends-its-partnership-agreement/|title=Deportivo Alav\u00e9s and NK Rude\u0161 ends its partnership agreement\n|publisher=[[NK Rude\u0161]]|date=15 June 2018|accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sochaux===\nIn April 2018, Alav\u00e9s signed an agreement with French club [[FC Sochaux-Montb\u00e9liard]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/04/25/primera/1524644483_024102.html |title=Oficial: el Alav\u00e9s firma una alianza con el Sochaux franc\u00e9s|trans-title=Official: El Alav\u00e9s signs an alliance with the French Sochaux|language=es |work=[[Diario AS]]|author=Javier Lekuona|date=25 April 2018|accessdate=24 January 2019 }}</ref> however the partnership lasted only a few months, ending abruptly in December of the same year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/alaves/2018/12/14/5c1402f3268e3e57288b4655.html|title=Alav\u00e9s y Sochaux separan sus caminos |trans-title=Alav\u00e9s and Sochaux separate their paths|language=es |work=Marca |author=Jos\u00e9 Luis del Campo|date=14 December 2018|accessdate=24 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons-inline|Deportivo Alav\u00e9s}}\n*[http://www.alaves.com Official website] {{in lang|es}}\n* [http://www.laliga.es/en/laliga-santander/alaves Alav\u00e9s] at [[La Liga]] {{in lang|en|es}}\n* [http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/teams/club=69619/profile/index.html Alav\u00e9s] at [[UEFA]] {{in lang|en|es}}\n* [http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/e/e6.html Club profile at BDfutbol (match reports in each season)]\n*[http://alaves.elcorreo.com/historia/ Club history at ''El Correo'']{{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.futbolme.com/com/equipo.asp?id_equipo=535 Futbolme team profile] {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.glorioso.net ''Glorioso'', unofficial website] {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.terra.es/personal2/marueda/alaves/indexeng.htm Terra club info] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Deportivo Alav\u00e9s}}\n{{La Liga teamlist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alaves}}\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1921]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s| ]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in the Basque Country]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in Spain]]\n[[Category:La Liga clubs]]\n[[Category:Sport in Vitoria-Gasteiz]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:DATEUNIFY (audit)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deportivo_Alav%C3%A9s"}
{"title_page": "Xiaowei Zhuang", "text_new": "{{Chinese name|[[Zhuang (surname)|Zhuang]]}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Xiaowei Zhuang\n| native_name = \u5e84\u5c0f\u5a01\n| native_name_lang = zh\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|01|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Rugao]], [[Jiangsu]], [[China]]\n| death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| residence = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields = [[Biophysics]]\n| workplaces = [[Harvard University]]<br />[[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]]\n| patrons = \n| education = [[Suzhou High School]]<br />[[University of Science and Technology of China]]<br />[[University of California, Berkeley]]\n| thesis_title = <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year = <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = [[Stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy|Stochastic Optical Reconstruction Microscopy (STORM)]]\n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = [[MacArthur Fellows Program]], [[ACS Award in Pure Chemistry]], [[Max Delbruck Prize]], [[Sackler Prize]], [[NAS Award in Molecular Biology]], [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]], [[Vilcek Prize in Biomedical Science]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children = \n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Xiaowei Zhuang''' ({{zh|s=\u5e84\u5c0f\u5a01|t=\u838a\u5c0f\u5a01|p=Zhu\u0101ng Xi\u01ceow\u0113i}}; born January 1972) is a Chinese-American [[biophysicist]] who is the David B. Arnold Jr. Professor of Science, Professor of Chemistry and Chemical Biology, and Professor of Physics at [[Harvard University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zhuang.harvard.edu/ |title=Zhuang Lab Webpage |publisher=zhuang.harvard.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chemistry.harvard.edu/people/xiaowei-zhuang |title=Harvard Chemistry and Chemical Biology Faculty: Xiaowei Zhuang |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.physics.harvard.edu/people/facpages/zhuang |title=Harvard Physics Faculty: Xiaowei Zhuang |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> and an Investigator at the [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hhmi.org/research/investigators/zhuang_bio.html |title=HHMI Scientist Bio: Xiaowei Zhuang, Ph.D |publisher=Hhmi.org |date= |accessdate=2012-06-29}}</ref> She is best known for her work in the development of [[Stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy|Stochastic Optical Reconstruction Microscopy (STORM)]],<ref name=\"rust_2006\">{{cite journal| title=  Sub-diffraction-limit imaging by stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy (STORM)| doi=10.1038/nmeth929 | volume=3 | journal=Nature Methods | pages=793\u2013796| pmc=2700296 | pmid=16896339 | year=2006 | last1 = Rust | first1 = MJ | last2 = Bates | first2 = M | last3 = Zhuang | first3 = X}}</ref><ref name=\"bates_2007\">{{cite journal| title= Multicolor Super-Resolution Imaging with Photo-Switchable Fluorescent Probes| doi=10.1126/science.1146598 | volume=317 | journal=Science | pages=1749\u20131753| bibcode=2007Sci...317.1749B| pmc=2633025 | pmid=17702910 | date=September 2007 | last1 = Bates | first1 = M | last2 = Huang | first2 = B | last3 = Dempsey | first3 = GT | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref><ref name=\"huang_2008\">{{cite journal| title= Three-Dimensional Super-Resolution Imaging by Stochastic Optical Reconstruction Microscopy| doi=10.1126/science.1153529 | volume=319 | journal=Science | pages=810\u2013813| bibcode=2008Sci...319..810H| pmc=2633023 | pmid=18174397 | date=February 2008 | last1 = Huang | first1 = B | last2 = Wang | first2 = W | last3 = Bates | first3 = M | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref> a super-resolution fluorescence microscopy method, and the discoveries of novel cellular structures using STORM. She received a 2019 [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]] for developing super-resolution imaging techniques that get past the diffraction limits of traditional light microscopes, allowing scientists to visualize small structures within living cells.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://breakthroughprize.org/News/47|title=Breakthrough Prize \u2013 Winners of the 2019 Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences, Fundamental Physics and Mathematics Announced|website=breakthroughprize.org|language=en|access-date=2018-10-18}}</ref> She was elected a Member of the [[American Philosophical Society]] in 2019 and was awarded a [[Vilcek Foundation]] Prize in Biomedical Science in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vilcek.org/prizes/prize-recipients/xiaowei-zhuang/|title=Xiaowei Zhuang|website=Vilcek Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nZhuang's father Zhuang Lixian (\u5e84\u793c\u8d24)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mech.ustc.edu.cn/2012/1116/c4589a42143/page.htm|title=\u5e84\u793c\u8d24\u4e2d\u79d1\u5927\u4e3b\u9875}}</ref> and mother Zhu Renzhi (\u6731\u4ec1\u829d) are both professors at the [[University of Science and Technology of China]] (USTC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pmpi.ustc.edu.cn/2012/0925/c4118a38575/page.htm|title=\u6731\u4ec1\u829d\u4e2d\u79d1\u5927\u4e3b\u9875}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sciencenet.cn/htmlnews/2014/4/292321.shtm|title=\u7f8e\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u9662\u58eb\u5e84\u5c0f\u5a01\uff1a\u5e84\u5bb6\u6709\u5973\u662f\u5947\u624d}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ustc.edu.cn/kdb/200202/t20020220_62368.html|title=\u300a\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5927\u62a5\u300b551\u671f}}</ref>\n\nZhuang graduated from the [[University of Science and Technology of China|USTC]] with a B.S. in Physics in 1991. She obtained her Ph.D. in Physics from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1996 and conducted her thesis research under the supervision of Dr. [[Yuen-Ron Shen]]. In 1997-2001, she was a Chodorow Postdoctoral Fellow in the laboratory of Dr. [[Steven Chu]] at [[Stanford University]]. She started her faculty position in the Department of Chemistry and Chemical Biology and the Department of Physics at [[Harvard University]] in 2001 and was promoted to full professor in 2006.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2018/10/harvards-xiaowei-zhuang-awarded-2018-breakthrough-prize/|title=Xiaowei Zhuang receives 2019 Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences|date=2018-10-17|work=Harvard Gazette|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nShe was named a [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute|Howard Hughes Medical]] Investigator in 2005.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Research==\nZhuang's laboratory invented [[Stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy|Stochastic Optical Reconstruction Microscopy (STORM)]], a single-molecule-based super-resolution fluorescence microscopy method.<ref name=\"rust_2006\"/> The Zhuang laboratory demonstrated three-dimensional super-resolution imaging with STORM.<ref name=\"huang_2008\"/> The Zhuang laboratory also discovered several photoswitchable dye molecules<ref name=\"bates_2007\"/><ref>{{cite journal| title= Short-Range Spectroscopic Ruler Based on a Single-Molecule Optical Switch| doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.94.108101 | bibcode=2005PhRvL..94j8101B | volume=94 | journal=Physical Review Letters| arxiv=q-bio/0502012 | year=2005 | last1 = Bates | first1 = Mark | pmid=15783528 | pmc=2652517 | page=108101}}</ref><ref name=\"shim_2012\">{{cite journal| title= Super-resolution fluorescence imaging of organelles in live cells with photoswitchable membrane probes| doi=10.1073/pnas.1201882109 | volume=109 | journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | pages=13978\u201313983| bibcode=2012PNAS..10913978S| pmc=3435176 | pmid=22891300 | year=2012 | last1 = Shim | first1 = SH | last2 = Xia | first2 = C | last3 = Zhong | first3 = G | last4 = Babcock | first4 = HP | last5 = Vaughan | first5 = JC | last6 = Huang | first6 = B | last7 = Wang | first7 = X | last8 = Xu | first8 = C | last9 = Bi | first9 = GQ | last10 = Zhuang | first10 = X}}</ref> that enabled STORM imaging and demonstrated live-cell STORM imaging.<ref name=\"shim_2012\"/><ref>{{cite journal| title= Fast, three-dimensional super-resolution imaging of live cells| doi=10.1038/nmeth.1605 | volume=8 | journal=Nature Methods | pages=499\u2013505| pmc=3137767 | pmid=21552254 | date=June 2011 | last1 = Jones | first1 = SA | last2 = Shim | first2 = SH | last3 = He | first3 = J | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref>\n\nUsing STORM, Zhuang and colleagues have studied a variety of biological systems, ranging from single-cell organisms to complex brain tissues. These studies led to the discovery of novel cellular structures, such as the periodic membrane skeletons in the axons of neurons<ref>{{cite journal| title= Actin, Spectrin, and Associated Proteins Form a Periodic Cytoskeletal Structure in Axons| doi=10.1126/science.1232251 | volume=339 | journal=Science | pages=452\u2013456| bibcode=2013Sci...339..452X| pmc=3815867 | pmid=23239625 | year=2013 | last1 = Xu | first1 = K | last2 = Zhong | first2 = G | last3 = Zhuang | first3 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Developmental mechanism of the periodic membrane skeleton in axons| doi=10.7554/eLife.04581 | volume=3 | journal=eLife| pmc=4337613| pmid=25535840| year=2014 | last1 = Zhong | first1 = G | last2 = He | first2 = J | last3 = Zhou | first3 = R | last4 = Lorenzo | first4 = D | last5 = Babcock | first5 = HP | last6 = Bennett | first6 = V | last7 = Zhuang | first7 = X}}</ref> and provided insights into many other cellular structures.<ref>{{cite journal| title= Superresolution Imaging of Chemical Synapses in the Brain| doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2010.11.021 | volume=68 | journal=Neuron | pages=843\u2013856 | year=2010 | last1 = Dani | first1 = Adish | pmid=21144999 | pmc=3057101}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=Y. Doksani, J. Wu, T. de Lange, X. Zhuang, \"Super-resolution fluorescence imaging reveals TRF2-dependent t-loop formation\", Cell 155, 345-356 (2013) | doi=10.1016/j.cell.2013.09.048 | volume=155 | journal=Cell | pages=345\u2013356 | year=2013 | last1 = Doksani | first1 = Ylli | last2 = Wu | first2 = John Y. | last3 = de Lange | first3 = Titia | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = Xiaowei}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Structurally Distinct Ca2+ Signaling Domains of Sperm Flagella Orchestrate Tyrosine Phosphorylation and Motility| doi=10.1016/j.cell.2014.02.056 | volume=157 | journal=Cell | pages=808\u2013822 | year=2014 | last1 = Chung | first1 = Jean-Ju | last2 = Shim | first2 = Sang-Hee | last3 = Everley | first3 = Robert A. | last4 = Gygi | first4 = Steven P. | last5 = Zhuang | first5 = Xiaowei | last6 = Clapham | first6 = David E.}}</ref>\n\nThe Zhuang laboratory invented a single-cell transcriptome imaging method, MERFISH (multiplexed error-robust fluorescence in situ hybridization), which allows numerous RNA species to be imaged and quantified in single cells in their native context.<ref>{{cite journal| title= Spatially resolved, highly multiplexed RNA profiling in single cells| doi=10.1126/science.aaa6090 | volume=348 | journal=Science | page=aaa6090 | year=2015 | last1 = Chen | first1 = K. H. | last2 = Boettiger | first2 = A. N. | last3 = Moffitt | first3 = J. R. | last4 = Wang | first4 = S. | last5 = Zhuang | first5 = X. | pmid=25858977 | pmc=4662681}}</ref> Zhuang and colleagues used single-molecule FRET to study biomolecules and molecular complexes<ref>{{cite journal| title= A Single-Molecule Study of RNA Catalysis and Folding| doi=10.1126/science.288.5473.2048 | volume=288 | journal=Science | pages=2048\u20132051| bibcode=2000Sci...288.2048Z | year=2000 | last1 = Zhuang | first1 = X.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Stepwise protein-mediated RNA folding directs assembly of telomerase ribonucleoprotein| doi=10.1038/nature05600 | volume=446 | journal=Nature | pages=458\u2013461| bibcode=2007Natur.446..458S| pmc=2720403 | pmid=17322903 | year=2007 | last1 = Stone | first1 = MD | last2 = Mihalusova | first2 = M | last3 = O'Connor | first3 = CM | last4 = Prathapam | first4 = R | last5 = Collins | first5 = K | last6 = Zhuang | first6 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Dynamic binding orientations direct activity of HIV reverse transcriptase| doi=10.1038/nature06941 | volume=453 | journal=Nature | pages=184\u2013189| bibcode=2008Natur.453..184A| pmc=2655135 | pmid=18464735 | year=2008 | last1 = Abbondanzieri | first1 = EA | last2 = Bokinsky | first2 = G | last3 = Rausch | first3 = JW | last4 = Zhang | first4 = JX | last5 = Le Grice | first5 = SF | last6 = Zhuang | first6 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=T. Blosser, J. Yang, M. Stone, G. Narlikar, X. Zhuang, \"Dynamics of Nucleosome Remodeling by Individual ACF Complexes\", Nature 462, 1022-1027 (2009) | doi=10.1038/nature08627 | volume=462 | journal=Nature | pages=1022\u20131027| bibcode=2009Natur.462.1022B | pmc=2835771 | pmid=20033040 | year=2009 | last1 = Blosser | first1 = TR | last2 = Yang | first2 = JG | last3 = Stone | first3 = MD | last4 = Narlikar | first4 = GJ | last5 = Zhuang | first5 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Histone H4 tail mediates allosteric regulation of nucleosome remodelling by linker DNA| doi=10.1038/nature13380 | volume=512 | journal=Nature | pages=213\u2013217| bibcode=2014Natur.512..213H| pmc=4134374 | pmid=25043036 | year=2014 | last1 = Hwang | first1 = WL | last2 = Deindl | first2 = S | last3 = Harada | first3 = BT | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref> and developed single-virus tracking methods to study virus-cell interactions.<ref>{{cite journal| title= Visualizing infection of individual influenza viruses| doi=10.1073/pnas.0832269100 | volume=100 | journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | pages=9280\u20139285| bibcode=2003PNAS..100.9280L | year=2003 | last1 = Lakadamyali | first1 = M. | pmid=12883000 | pmc=170909}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Assembly of endocytic machinery around individual influenza viruses during viral entry| doi=10.1038/nsmb769 | volume=11 | journal=Nature Structural & Molecular Biology | pages=567\u2013573| pmc=2748740 | pmid=15122347 | year=2004 | last1 = Rust | first1 = MJ | last2 = Lakadamyali | first2 = M | last3 = Zhang | first3 = F | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Virus trafficking \u2013 learning from single-virus tracking| doi=10.1038/nrmicro1615 | volume=5 | journal=Nature Reviews Microbiology | pages=197\u2013208| pmc=2740720 | pmid=17304249 | year=2007 | last1 = Brandenburg | first1 = B | last2 = Zhuang | first2 = X}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n* 2020: [[Vilcek Foundation]] Prize in [[Biomedical sciences|Biomedical Science]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vilcek.org/prizes/prize-recipients/xiaowei-zhuang/|title=Xiaowei Zhuang|website=Vilcek Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n* 2019: [[Pearl Meister Greengard Prize]]<ref> {{cite web|url=https://www.rockefeller.edu/greengard-prize/2019-ceremony/|title=PEARL MEISTER GREENGARD PRIZE|publisher=Rockefeller University|accessdate= 8 October 2019}} </ref>\n* 2019: [[NAS Award for Scientific Discovery]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Xiaowei Zhuang |url=http://www.nasonline.org/programs/awards/2019-nas-awards/Zhuang.html |website=www.nasonline.org}}</ref>\n* 2019: [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]]<ref name=\":1\" /> \n* 2018: [[Heineken Prizes|Dr. H.P. Heineken Prize for Biochemistry and Biophysics]], [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Xiaowei Zhuang awarded Heineken Prize |url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/newsplus/xiaowei-zhuang-awarded-prestigious-heineken-prize/|date=2018-4-25|work=Harvard Gazette|access-date=2020-4-1}}</ref>\n* 2018: Pittsburgh Analytical Chemistry Award<ref>https://pittcon.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Pittsburgh-Analytical-Chemistry-Previous-Recipients.pdf</ref>\n* 2017: Honorary doctorate, Delft University of Technology\n* 2017: Lennart Nilsson Award, Karolinska Institute, Sweden\n* 2016: Doctor of Philosophy Honoris Causa, Stockholm University\n* 2015: Foreign academician of the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]]<ref>http://www.cas.cn/tz/201512/t20151207_4488383.shtml \u5173\u4e8e\u516c\u5e032015\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u9662\u58eb\u589e\u9009\u5f53\u9009\u9662\u58eb\u540d\u5355\u7684\u516c\u544a</ref>\n* 2015: [[NAS Award in Molecular Biology]]\n* 2013: Member [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n* 2012: Member [[National Academy of Sciences]]\n* 2012: Fellow [[American Physical Society]]\n* 2012: Fellow [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n* 2011: [[Sackler Prize]]\n* 2010: [[Max Delbruck Prize]]\n* 2008: [[Coblentz Award]]\n* 2007: [[ACS Award in Pure Chemistry]]\n* 2004: [[Sloan Fellowship]]\n* 2003: [[Packard Fellowship]]\n* 2003: [[MacArthur Fellows Program]]\n* 2003: [[Beckman Young Investigators Award]]<ref name=RecipientSearch>{{cite web|title=Zhuang, Xiaowei |url=http://www.beckman-foundation.org/beckman-young-investigators/xiaowei-zhuang?A=SearchResult&SearchID=3906844&ObjectID=4732091&ObjectType=35|website=Arnold and Mabel Beckman Foundation|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Breakthrough Prize laureates}}\n{{Heineken Prizes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhuang, Xiaowei}}\n\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American biophysicists]]\n[[Category:American scientists of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Howard Hughes Medical Investigators]]\n[[Category:MacArthur Fellows]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Science and Technology of China alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Foreign members of the Chinese Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Nantong]]\n[[Category:Chinese emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Chinese biophysicists]]\n[[Category:American women biologists]]\n[[Category:Chinese women biologists]]\n[[Category:American women physicists]]\n[[Category:Chinese women physicists]]\n[[Category:Physicists from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Educators from Nantong]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Philosophical Society]]\n[[Category:Biologists from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:People from Rugao]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese name|[[Zhuang (surname)|Zhuang]]}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Xiaowei Zhuang\n| native_name = \u5e84\u5c0f\u5a01\n| native_name_lang = zh\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|01|21}}\n| birth_place = [[Rugao]], [[Jiangsu]], [[China]]\n| death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| residence = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = \n| fields = [[Biophysics]]\n| workplaces = [[Harvard University]]<br />[[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]]\n| patrons = \n| education = [[Suzhou High School]]<br />[[University of Science and Technology of China]]<br />[[University of California, Berkeley]]\n| thesis_title = <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year = <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = [[Stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy|Stochastic Optical Reconstruction Microscopy (STORM)]]\n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = [[MacArthur Fellows Program]], [[ACS Award in Pure Chemistry]], [[Max Delbruck Prize]], [[Sackler Prize]], [[NAS Award in Molecular Biology]], [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]], [[Vilcek Prize in Biomedical Science]]\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children = \n| signature = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Xiaowei Zhuang''' ({{zh|s=\u5e84\u5c0f\u5a01|t=\u838a\u5c0f\u5a01|p=Zhu\u0101ng Xi\u01ceow\u0113i}}; born January 1972) is a Chinese-American [[biophysicist]] who is the David B. Arnold Jr. Professor of Science, Professor of Chemistry and Chemical Biology, and Professor of Physics at [[Harvard University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zhuang.harvard.edu/ |title=Zhuang Lab Webpage |publisher=zhuang.harvard.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chemistry.harvard.edu/people/xiaowei-zhuang |title=Harvard Chemistry and Chemical Biology Faculty: Xiaowei Zhuang |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.physics.harvard.edu/people/facpages/zhuang |title=Harvard Physics Faculty: Xiaowei Zhuang |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> and an Investigator at the [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hhmi.org/research/investigators/zhuang_bio.html |title=HHMI Scientist Bio: Xiaowei Zhuang, Ph.D |publisher=Hhmi.org |date= |accessdate=2012-06-29}}</ref> She is best known for her work in the development of [[Stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy|Stochastic Optical Reconstruction Microscopy (STORM)]],<ref name=\"rust_2006\">{{cite journal| title=  Sub-diffraction-limit imaging by stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy (STORM)| doi=10.1038/nmeth929 | volume=3 | journal=Nature Methods | pages=793\u2013796| pmc=2700296 | pmid=16896339 | year=2006 | last1 = Rust | first1 = MJ | last2 = Bates | first2 = M | last3 = Zhuang | first3 = X}}</ref><ref name=\"bates_2007\">{{cite journal| title= Multicolor Super-Resolution Imaging with Photo-Switchable Fluorescent Probes| doi=10.1126/science.1146598 | volume=317 | journal=Science | pages=1749\u20131753| bibcode=2007Sci...317.1749B| pmc=2633025 | pmid=17702910 | date=September 2007 | last1 = Bates | first1 = M | last2 = Huang | first2 = B | last3 = Dempsey | first3 = GT | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref><ref name=\"huang_2008\">{{cite journal| title= Three-Dimensional Super-Resolution Imaging by Stochastic Optical Reconstruction Microscopy| doi=10.1126/science.1153529 | volume=319 | journal=Science | pages=810\u2013813| bibcode=2008Sci...319..810H| pmc=2633023 | pmid=18174397 | date=February 2008 | last1 = Huang | first1 = B | last2 = Wang | first2 = W | last3 = Bates | first3 = M | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref> a super-resolution fluorescence microscopy method, and the discoveries of novel cellular structures using STORM. She received a 2019 [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]] for developing super-resolution imaging techniques that get past the diffraction limits of traditional light microscopes, allowing scientists to visualize small structures within living cells.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://breakthroughprize.org/News/47|title=Breakthrough Prize \u2013 Winners of the 2019 Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences, Fundamental Physics and Mathematics Announced|website=breakthroughprize.org|language=en|access-date=2018-10-18}}</ref> She was elected a Member of the [[American Philosophical Society]] in 2019 and was awarded a [[Vilcek Foundation]] Prize in Biomedical Science in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vilcek.org/prizes/prize-recipients/xiaowei-zhuang/|title=Xiaowei Zhuang|website=Vilcek Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nZhuang's father Zhuang Lixian (\u5e84\u793c\u8d24)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mech.ustc.edu.cn/2012/1116/c4589a42143/page.htm|title=\u5e84\u793c\u8d24\u4e2d\u79d1\u5927\u4e3b\u9875}}</ref> and mother Zhu Renzhi (\u6731\u4ec1\u829d) are both professors at the [[University of Science and Technology of China]] (USTC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pmpi.ustc.edu.cn/2012/0925/c4118a38575/page.htm|title=\u6731\u4ec1\u829d\u4e2d\u79d1\u5927\u4e3b\u9875}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sciencenet.cn/htmlnews/2014/4/292321.shtm|title=\u7f8e\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u9662\u58eb\u5e84\u5c0f\u5a01\uff1a\u5e84\u5bb6\u6709\u5973\u662f\u5947\u624d}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ustc.edu.cn/kdb/200202/t20020220_62368.html|title=\u300a\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5927\u62a5\u300b551\u671f}}</ref>\n\nZhuang graduated from the [[University of Science and Technology of China|USTC]] with a B.S. in Physics in 1991. She obtained her Ph.D. in Physics from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1996 and conducted her thesis research under the supervision of Dr. [[Yuen-Ron Shen]]. In 1997-2001, she was a Chodorow Postdoctoral Fellow in the laboratory of Dr. [[Steven Chu]] at [[Stanford University]]. She started her faculty position in the Department of Chemistry and Chemical Biology and the Department of Physics at [[Harvard University]] in 2001 and was promoted to full professor in 2006.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2018/10/harvards-xiaowei-zhuang-awarded-2018-breakthrough-prize/|title=Harvard\u2019s Xiaowei Zhuang awarded 2018 Breakthrough Prize|date=2018-10-17|work=Harvard Gazette|access-date=2018-10-18|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nShe was named a [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute|Howard Hughes Medical]] Investigator in 2005.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Research==\nZhuang's laboratory invented [[Stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy|Stochastic Optical Reconstruction Microscopy (STORM)]], a single-molecule-based super-resolution fluorescence microscopy method.<ref name=\"rust_2006\"/> The Zhuang laboratory demonstrated three-dimensional super-resolution imaging with STORM.<ref name=\"huang_2008\"/> The Zhuang laboratory also discovered several photoswitchable dye molecules<ref name=\"bates_2007\"/><ref>{{cite journal| title= Short-Range Spectroscopic Ruler Based on a Single-Molecule Optical Switch| doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.94.108101 | bibcode=2005PhRvL..94j8101B | volume=94 | journal=Physical Review Letters| arxiv=q-bio/0502012 | year=2005 | last1 = Bates | first1 = Mark | pmid=15783528 | pmc=2652517 | page=108101}}</ref><ref name=\"shim_2012\">{{cite journal| title= Super-resolution fluorescence imaging of organelles in live cells with photoswitchable membrane probes| doi=10.1073/pnas.1201882109 | volume=109 | journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | pages=13978\u201313983| bibcode=2012PNAS..10913978S| pmc=3435176 | pmid=22891300 | year=2012 | last1 = Shim | first1 = SH | last2 = Xia | first2 = C | last3 = Zhong | first3 = G | last4 = Babcock | first4 = HP | last5 = Vaughan | first5 = JC | last6 = Huang | first6 = B | last7 = Wang | first7 = X | last8 = Xu | first8 = C | last9 = Bi | first9 = GQ | last10 = Zhuang | first10 = X}}</ref> that enabled STORM imaging and demonstrated live-cell STORM imaging.<ref name=\"shim_2012\"/><ref>{{cite journal| title= Fast, three-dimensional super-resolution imaging of live cells| doi=10.1038/nmeth.1605 | volume=8 | journal=Nature Methods | pages=499\u2013505| pmc=3137767 | pmid=21552254 | date=June 2011 | last1 = Jones | first1 = SA | last2 = Shim | first2 = SH | last3 = He | first3 = J | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref>\n\nUsing STORM, Zhuang and colleagues have studied a variety of biological systems, ranging from single-cell organisms to complex brain tissues. These studies led to the discovery of novel cellular structures, such as the periodic membrane skeletons in the axons of neurons<ref>{{cite journal| title= Actin, Spectrin, and Associated Proteins Form a Periodic Cytoskeletal Structure in Axons| doi=10.1126/science.1232251 | volume=339 | journal=Science | pages=452\u2013456| bibcode=2013Sci...339..452X| pmc=3815867 | pmid=23239625 | year=2013 | last1 = Xu | first1 = K | last2 = Zhong | first2 = G | last3 = Zhuang | first3 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Developmental mechanism of the periodic membrane skeleton in axons| doi=10.7554/eLife.04581 | volume=3 | journal=eLife| pmc=4337613| pmid=25535840| year=2014 | last1 = Zhong | first1 = G | last2 = He | first2 = J | last3 = Zhou | first3 = R | last4 = Lorenzo | first4 = D | last5 = Babcock | first5 = HP | last6 = Bennett | first6 = V | last7 = Zhuang | first7 = X}}</ref> and provided insights into many other cellular structures.<ref>{{cite journal| title= Superresolution Imaging of Chemical Synapses in the Brain| doi=10.1016/j.neuron.2010.11.021 | volume=68 | journal=Neuron | pages=843\u2013856 | year=2010 | last1 = Dani | first1 = Adish | pmid=21144999 | pmc=3057101}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=Y. Doksani, J. Wu, T. de Lange, X. Zhuang, \"Super-resolution fluorescence imaging reveals TRF2-dependent t-loop formation\", Cell 155, 345-356 (2013) | doi=10.1016/j.cell.2013.09.048 | volume=155 | journal=Cell | pages=345\u2013356 | year=2013 | last1 = Doksani | first1 = Ylli | last2 = Wu | first2 = John Y. | last3 = de Lange | first3 = Titia | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = Xiaowei}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Structurally Distinct Ca2+ Signaling Domains of Sperm Flagella Orchestrate Tyrosine Phosphorylation and Motility| doi=10.1016/j.cell.2014.02.056 | volume=157 | journal=Cell | pages=808\u2013822 | year=2014 | last1 = Chung | first1 = Jean-Ju | last2 = Shim | first2 = Sang-Hee | last3 = Everley | first3 = Robert A. | last4 = Gygi | first4 = Steven P. | last5 = Zhuang | first5 = Xiaowei | last6 = Clapham | first6 = David E.}}</ref>\n\nThe Zhuang laboratory invented a single-cell transcriptome imaging method, MERFISH (multiplexed error-robust fluorescence in situ hybridization), which allows numerous RNA species to be imaged and quantified in single cells in their native context.<ref>{{cite journal| title= Spatially resolved, highly multiplexed RNA profiling in single cells| doi=10.1126/science.aaa6090 | volume=348 | journal=Science | page=aaa6090 | year=2015 | last1 = Chen | first1 = K. H. | last2 = Boettiger | first2 = A. N. | last3 = Moffitt | first3 = J. R. | last4 = Wang | first4 = S. | last5 = Zhuang | first5 = X. | pmid=25858977 | pmc=4662681}}</ref> Zhuang and colleagues used single-molecule FRET to study biomolecules and molecular complexes<ref>{{cite journal| title= A Single-Molecule Study of RNA Catalysis and Folding| doi=10.1126/science.288.5473.2048 | volume=288 | journal=Science | pages=2048\u20132051| bibcode=2000Sci...288.2048Z | year=2000 | last1 = Zhuang | first1 = X.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Stepwise protein-mediated RNA folding directs assembly of telomerase ribonucleoprotein| doi=10.1038/nature05600 | volume=446 | journal=Nature | pages=458\u2013461| bibcode=2007Natur.446..458S| pmc=2720403 | pmid=17322903 | year=2007 | last1 = Stone | first1 = MD | last2 = Mihalusova | first2 = M | last3 = O'Connor | first3 = CM | last4 = Prathapam | first4 = R | last5 = Collins | first5 = K | last6 = Zhuang | first6 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Dynamic binding orientations direct activity of HIV reverse transcriptase| doi=10.1038/nature06941 | volume=453 | journal=Nature | pages=184\u2013189| bibcode=2008Natur.453..184A| pmc=2655135 | pmid=18464735 | year=2008 | last1 = Abbondanzieri | first1 = EA | last2 = Bokinsky | first2 = G | last3 = Rausch | first3 = JW | last4 = Zhang | first4 = JX | last5 = Le Grice | first5 = SF | last6 = Zhuang | first6 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=T. Blosser, J. Yang, M. Stone, G. Narlikar, X. Zhuang, \"Dynamics of Nucleosome Remodeling by Individual ACF Complexes\", Nature 462, 1022-1027 (2009) | doi=10.1038/nature08627 | volume=462 | journal=Nature | pages=1022\u20131027| bibcode=2009Natur.462.1022B | pmc=2835771 | pmid=20033040 | year=2009 | last1 = Blosser | first1 = TR | last2 = Yang | first2 = JG | last3 = Stone | first3 = MD | last4 = Narlikar | first4 = GJ | last5 = Zhuang | first5 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Histone H4 tail mediates allosteric regulation of nucleosome remodelling by linker DNA| doi=10.1038/nature13380 | volume=512 | journal=Nature | pages=213\u2013217| bibcode=2014Natur.512..213H| pmc=4134374 | pmid=25043036 | year=2014 | last1 = Hwang | first1 = WL | last2 = Deindl | first2 = S | last3 = Harada | first3 = BT | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref> and developed single-virus tracking methods to study virus-cell interactions.<ref>{{cite journal| title= Visualizing infection of individual influenza viruses| doi=10.1073/pnas.0832269100 | volume=100 | journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | pages=9280\u20139285| bibcode=2003PNAS..100.9280L | year=2003 | last1 = Lakadamyali | first1 = M. | pmid=12883000 | pmc=170909}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Assembly of endocytic machinery around individual influenza viruses during viral entry| doi=10.1038/nsmb769 | volume=11 | journal=Nature Structural & Molecular Biology | pages=567\u2013573| pmc=2748740 | pmid=15122347 | year=2004 | last1 = Rust | first1 = MJ | last2 = Lakadamyali | first2 = M | last3 = Zhang | first3 = F | last4 = Zhuang | first4 = X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title= Virus trafficking \u2013 learning from single-virus tracking| doi=10.1038/nrmicro1615 | volume=5 | journal=Nature Reviews Microbiology | pages=197\u2013208| pmc=2740720 | pmid=17304249 | year=2007 | last1 = Brandenburg | first1 = B | last2 = Zhuang | first2 = X}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n* 2020: [[Vilcek Foundation]] Prize in [[Biomedical sciences|Biomedical Science]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vilcek.org/prizes/prize-recipients/xiaowei-zhuang/|title=Xiaowei Zhuang|website=Vilcek Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n*2019: [[Pearl Meister Greengard Prize]]<ref> {{cite web|url=https://www.rockefeller.edu/greengard-prize/2019-ceremony/|title=PEARL MEISTER GREENGARD PRIZE|publisher=Rockefeller University|accessdate= 8 October 2019}} </ref>\n* 2019: [[NAS Award for Scientific Discovery]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Xiaowei Zhuang |url=http://www.nasonline.org/programs/awards/2019-nas-awards/Zhuang.html |website=www.nasonline.org}}</ref>\n* 2019: [[Breakthrough Prize in Life Sciences]]<ref name=\":1\" /> \n* 2018: [[Heineken Prizes|Dr. H.P. Heineken Prize for Biochemistry and Biophysics]], [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Xiaowei Zhuang awarded Heineken Prize |url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/newsplus/xiaowei-zhuang-awarded-prestigious-heineken-prize/|date=2018-4-25|work=Harvard Gazette|access-date=2020-4-1|}}</ref>\n* 2018: Pittsburgh Analytical Chemistry Award<ref>https://pittcon.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Pittsburgh-Analytical-Chemistry-Previous-Recipients.pdf</ref>\n* 2017: Honorary doctorate, Delft University of Technology\n* 2017: Lennart Nilsson Award, Karolinska Institute, Sweden\n* 2016: Doctor of Philosophy Honoris Causa, Stockholm University\n* 2015: Foreign academician of the [[Chinese Academy of Sciences]]<ref>http://www.cas.cn/tz/201512/t20151207_4488383.shtml \u5173\u4e8e\u516c\u5e032015\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u79d1\u5b66\u9662\u9662\u58eb\u589e\u9009\u5f53\u9009\u9662\u58eb\u540d\u5355\u7684\u516c\u544a</ref>\n* 2015: [[NAS Award in Molecular Biology]]\n* 2013: Member [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n* 2012: Member [[National Academy of Sciences]]\n* 2012: Fellow [[American Physical Society]]\n* 2012: Fellow [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n* 2011: [[Sackler Prize]]\n* 2010: [[Max Delbruck Prize]]\n* 2008: [[Coblentz Award]]\n* 2007: [[ACS Award in Pure Chemistry]]\n* 2004: [[Sloan Fellowship]]\n* 2003: [[Packard Fellowship]]\n* 2003: [[MacArthur Fellows Program]]\n* 2003: [[Beckman Young Investigators Award]]<ref name=RecipientSearch>{{cite web|title=Zhuang, Xiaowei |url=http://www.beckman-foundation.org/beckman-young-investigators/xiaowei-zhuang?A=SearchResult&SearchID=3906844&ObjectID=4732091&ObjectType=35|website=Arnold and Mabel Beckman Foundation|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Breakthrough Prize laureates}}\n{{Heineken Prizes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhuang, Xiaowei}}\n\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American biophysicists]]\n[[Category:American scientists of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Howard Hughes Medical Investigators]]\n[[Category:MacArthur Fellows]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Science and Technology of China alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Foreign members of the Chinese Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Nantong]]\n[[Category:Chinese emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Chinese biophysicists]]\n[[Category:American women biologists]]\n[[Category:Chinese women biologists]]\n[[Category:American women physicists]]\n[[Category:Chinese women physicists]]\n[[Category:Physicists from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Educators from Nantong]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Philosophical Society]]\n[[Category:Biologists from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:People from Rugao]]\n", "name_user": "Poppopsun", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xiaowei_Zhuang"}
{"title_page": "List of FIDE chess world number ones", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\nA total of seven [[chess player]]s have been the chess world number one on the official [[FIDE]] rating list since it was first published in July 1971.<ref name=\"History of Elo ratings 1971-2001\">[http://www.olimpbase.org/index.html?http%3A%2F%2Fwww.olimpbase.org%2FElo%2Fsummary.html History of Elo ratings 1971-2001] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305002754/http://www.olimpbase.org/index.html?http:%2F%2Fwww.olimpbase.org%2FElo%2Fsummary.html |date=2016-03-05 }}, OlimpBase</ref>\n\nThe first world number one, in July 1971, was [[Bobby Fischer]]. In January 1976 [[Anatoly Karpov]] became the highest-rated player on the FIDE list, FIDE having dropped Fischer (whose rating was higher than Karpov's) from the list [[Bobby Fischer#Sudden obscurity|due to inactivity]]. In January 1984, the third world number one was [[Garry Kasparov]]. Anatoly Karpov briefly held the world number one ranking in July 1985, and the fourth world number one, [[Vladimir Kramnik]], briefly held the ranking in January 1996. Other than these two brief periods, Kasparov dominated for some 22 years from 1984 until his retirement from professional chess on 10 March 2005. In January 1990, he surpassed Fischer's peak of 2785 and became the first player ever to achieve a 2800 rating. In July 1999, he reached his peak rating, 2851. This was the highest FIDE rating in history until January 2013, when it was surpassed by [[Magnus Carlsen]].\n\nOn Kasparov's retirement, the world number one ranking passed to [[Veselin Topalov]], since Kasparov was removed from the rating list in April 2006 due to inactivity. In April 2007, [[Viswanathan Anand]] became the sixth player to top the rankings.<ref>[http://www.chess.co.uk/twic/ap2007.html FIDE January 2007 Rating List: Top 100], The Week In Chess</ref> Kramnik briefly returned to the number one ranking in January 2008, but was again joint number one by rating, being placed first in the list due to having played more games in the rating period in question. For most of the period April 2007 to November 2009, the top ranking was held by either Anand or Topalov. The seventh and current world number one is [[Magnus Carlsen]], who first achieved this ranking in the January 2010 list, and has been world number one since July 2011 after having lost and reclaimed the position from Anand during 2010 and 2011.\n\n==Publication details==\n{{More citations needed section|date=August 2019}}\n\nThere were unofficial lists in 1964, 1969, 1970 and January 1971, as the [[Elo rating]] system was first introduced.{{where|date=August 2019}}\n\nFrom 1971 to 1980, there was one main rating list published each year (for a total of 10), initially published in July from 1971 to 1973, then once in May (1974), before switching to annual publication in January from 1975 to 1980 (in this period, some supplements and amendments were also published).\n\nFrom 1981 to July 2000, two lists per year were published, in January and July (for a total of 39 lists). In July 2000, the publication schedule was increased to four times a year (January, April, July, October) operating from July 2000 to July 2009 (for a total of 36 lists). In July 2009, the publication schedule was increased again, to six times a year (January, March, May, July, September, November) operating from July 2009 to July 2012 (for a total of 18 lists). In July 2012 the publication schedule was increased again to the current monthly schedule.\n\nPublication of the rating lists in the 1970s and 1980s was in ''[[Chess Informant]]'' and other chess publications. The number of games played by individuals during the rating period was added to the lists from July 1985 onwards. Player ID numbers were used from January 1990. From January 1999, the practice of rounding to the nearest five Elo points was discontinued, and ratings were then rounded to the nearest Elo point for publication. From July 2000 onwards, the ratings are available from the FIDE website.<ref name=\"History of Elo ratings 1971-2001\"/>\n\nIn January 2010 former World Champion [[Boris Spassky]] criticized the current emphasis on ratings rather than World Champions.<ref>[http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/kings_don_rule_d1N8Uq7aXJtkGMsU5SNi3K Spassky ''Kings Don't Rule'']</ref> Although Spassky was World Champion during the inception of the FIDE rankings in 1971, he never became the number-one rated player in the world; since July 1971 he and Vladimir Kramnik are the only undisputed World Champions to never become ranked world number-one during their tenure as champions.\n\n==List of world number ones==\n=== Top players (list) ===\nThe following is a list of the players ranked number one on the FIDE rating system from the first official list in July 1971 to the present day, along with their ratings during the periods in question.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! January !! February !! March !! April !! May !! June !! July !! August !! September !!  October !!  November !! December\n|-\n| 1971 || colspan=6 | ''before official FIDE ratings'' || colspan=6 | {{flagicon|United States}} [[Bobby Fischer|Fischer]] (2760)\n|-\n| 1972 || colspan=6 | || colspan=6 | {{flagicon|United States}} [[Bobby Fischer|Fischer]] (2785)\n|-\n| 1973 || colspan=6 | || colspan=6 | {{flagicon|United States}} [[Bobby Fischer|Fischer]] (2780)\n|-\n| 1974 || colspan=4 | || colspan=8 | {{flagicon|United States}} [[Bobby Fischer|Fischer]] (2780)\n|-\n| 1975 || colspan=12 | {{flagicon|United States}} [[Bobby Fischer|Fischer]] (2780)\n|-\n| 1976 || colspan=12 | {{flagicon|Soviet Union|1955}} [[Anatoly Karpov|Karpov]] (2695)\n|-\n| 1977 || colspan=12 | {{flagicon|Soviet Union|1955}} Karpov (2690)\n|-\n| 1978 || colspan=6 | {{flagicon|Soviet Union|1955}} Karpov (2725)  || colspan=6 | ''supplementary list''\n|-\n| 1979 || colspan=6 | {{flagicon|Soviet Union|1955}} Karpov (2705)  || colspan