{"title_page": "Bryan Mosley", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Bryan Mosley\n| image                   = \n| imagesize               = 200px\n| caption                 = Brian as [[Alf Roberts]] on [[Coronation Street]]\n| birth_date               = {{Birth date|1931|8|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place              = [[Leeds]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date               = {{death date and age|1999|2|9|1931|8|25|df=y}}\n| death_place              = [[Shipley, West Yorkshire|Shipley]], [[West Yorkshire]], England<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-bryan-mosley-1070036.html|location=London, UK|work=The Independent|first=Anthony|last=Hayward|title=Obituary: Bryan Mosley|date=11 February 1999}}</ref>\n| education               = Leeds Central High School\n| occupation              = [[Actor]]\n| yearsactive             = 1960\u20131999\n| spouse                  = {{marriage|Norma Bowes|1956|9 February 1999}}; (his death)\n| children                = 6}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n'''Bryan Mosley''' (25 August 1931 \u2013 9 February 1999) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[actor]], known best as grocer [[Alf Roberts]] in the long-running [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Coronation Street]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Leeds]], he attended Leeds Central High School and held a childhood ambition to become a missionary. Instead he won a scholarship to [[Leeds Arts University|Leeds College of Art]] (1944\u201346) and afterwards worked as a commercial artist. He also worked in a bookshop and sold books door-to-door.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-bryan-mosley-1070036.html|title=Obituary: Bryan Mosley|author=Anthony Hayward|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=11 February 1999|accessdate=29 August 2010|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Conscription in the United Kingdom #After 1945|national service]] in the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]], working in [[air traffic control]] in Scotland, he trained as an actor at the [[Bradford Playhouse|Bradford Civic Theatre]] and [[Esme Church]]'s Northern Theatre School. {{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n==Coronation Street==\nMosley joined the cast of ''[[Coronation Street]]'' in 1961 and made recurrent appearances until 1963. He returned to the series briefly in 1967 before rejoining as a regular cast member in 1971. Mosley's appearances in the soap opera became less frequent following a serious heart attack in 1991. Alf Roberts made his last appearance on [[New Year's Day]] 1999, dying peacefully on screen in his sleep. Mosley died just weeks later of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] in [[Shipley, West Yorkshire|Shipley]], [[West Yorkshire]] aged 67.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|0608818|Bryan Mosley}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the show's 40th anniversary celebrations, heritage plaques were unveiled outside the [[Granada Studios]] in 2000 to four of the soap opera's stars, including Mosley. The other plaques commemorated the lives of [[Doris Speed]], [[Pat Phoenix]] and [[Violet Carson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/988365.stm|title=Former Corrie stars remembered|work=[[BBC News]]|date=24 October 2000|accessdate=29 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Other notable roles==\nMosley made his screen debut in ''[[A Kind of Loving (film)|A Kind of Loving]]'' (1962). He also appeared in ''[[Get Carter]]'' (1971) playing local gangster Cliff Brumby. He is famously killed by Jack Carter ([[Michael Caine]]) who beats him up and throws him from the roof of the [[Trinity Square Gateshead|Trinity Square]] [[multi-storey car park]] in [[Gateshead]], after discovering Brumby's involvement in his brother's death. He played alien dignitary Malpha and a Prop Man on a film set in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' story \"[[The Daleks' Master Plan]]\" in 1965 and made two appearances in ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]''. Mosley also had a small role as the pub landlord in ''[[Queenie's Castle]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n==Fight arranger==\nHe was also a fencer and a stage and film fight arranger. He fenced with [[Terence Stamp]] in the film ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]].'' He was a founder member of the Society of British Fight Directors and he arranged the ''Get Carter'' fight with Caine. Mosley was sometimes credited as '''Buddy Windrush'''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nBryan Mosley wed Norma Bowes in 1956; the couple had six children.<ref name=\"imdb\"/> Mosley was a practising [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] who had made at least one pilgrimage to [[Lourdes]].<ref name=\"bbc\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/318396.stm Bryan Mosley obituary], bbc.co.uk; accessed 28 September 2014.</ref> He was awarded an honorary degree from the [[University of Bradford]].\n\nMosley died on 9 February 1999 aged 67.His wife died on 16 October 2011, aged 79.<ref>{{cite web |title=Norma Mosley |url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/announcements/deaths/deaths/9310826.norma_mosley/ |website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus |accessdate=26 June 2019 |language=en |date=18 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[A Kind of Loving (film)|A Kind of Loving]]'' || Bus Conductor || Uncredited\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[This Sporting Life]]'' || Man in bar || Uncredited\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[Billy Liar (film)|Billy Liar]]'' || Bit Part || Uncredited\n|-\n|1964|| ''[[Rattle of a Simple Man]]'' || Coach Organiser || Uncredited\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[Carry on Cowboy]]'' || Rider || Uncredited\n|-\n|1965|| ''[[Up Jumped a Swagman]]'' || Jo-Jo ||\n|-\n|1966|| ''[[Where the Bullets Fly]]'' || Connolly ||\n|-\n|1967|| ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]]'' || Barker ||\n|-\n|1968|| ''[[Charlie Bubbles]]'' || Herbert ||\n|-\n|1970|| ''[[Spring and Port Wine]]'' || ||\n|-\n|1971|| ''[[Get Carter]]'' || Cliff Brumby ||\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mosley, Bryan}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Leeds]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Leeds Arts University]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Bryan Mosley\n| image                   = \n| imagesize               = 200px\n| caption                 = Brian as [[Alf Roberts]] on [[Coronation Street]]\n| birth_date               = {{Birth date|1931|8|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place              = [[Leeds]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date               = {{death date and age|1999|2|9|1931|8|25|df=y}}\n| death_place              = [[Shipley, West Yorkshire|Shipley]], [[West Yorkshire]], England<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-bryan-mosley-1070036.html|location=London, UK|work=The Independent|first=Anthony|last=Hayward|title=Obituary: Bryan Mosley|date=11 February 1999}}</ref>\n| education               = Leeds Central High School\n| occupation              = [[Actor]]\n| yearsactive             = 1960\u20131999\n| spouse                  = {{marriage|Norma Bowes|1956|9 February 1999}}; (his death)\n| children                = 6}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n'''Bryan Mosley''' (25 August 1931 \u2013 9 February 1999) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[actor]], known best as grocer [[Alf Roberts]] in the long-running [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] [[soap opera]] ''[[Coronation Street]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Leeds]], he attended Leeds Central High School and held a childhood ambition to become a missionary. Instead he won a scholarship to [[Leeds Arts University|Leeds College of Art]] (1944\u201346) and afterwards worked as a commercial artist. He also worked in a bookshop and sold books door-to-door.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-bryan-mosley-1070036.html|title=Obituary: Bryan Mosley|author=Anthony Hayward|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=11 February 1999|accessdate=29 August 2010|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Conscription in the United Kingdom #After 1945|national service]] in the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]], working in [[air traffic control]] in Scotland, he trained as an actor at the [[Bradford Playhouse|Bradford Civic Theatre]] and [[Esme Church]]'s Northern Theatre School. {{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n==Coronation Street==\nMosley joined the cast of ''[[Coronation Street]]'' in 1961 and made recurrent appearances until 1963. He returned to the series briefly in 1967 before rejoining as a regular cast member in 1971. Mosley's appearances in the soap opera became less frequent following a serious heart attack in 1991. Alf Roberts made his last appearance on [[New Year's Day]] 1999, dying peacefully on screen in his sleep. Mosley died just weeks later of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] in [[Shipley, West Yorkshire|Shipley]], [[West Yorkshire]] aged 67.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|0608818|Bryan Mosley}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the show's 40th anniversary celebrations, heritage plaques were unveiled outside the [[Granada Studios]] in 2000 to four of the soap opera's stars, including Mosley. The other plaques commemorated the lives of [[Doris Speed]], [[Pat Phoenix]] and [[Violet Carson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/988365.stm|title=Former Corrie stars remembered|work=[[BBC News]]|date=24 October 2000|accessdate=29 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Other notable roles==\nMosley made his screen debut in ''[[A Kind of Loving (film)|A Kind of Loving]]'' (1962). He also appeared in ''[[Get Carter]]'' (1971) playing local gangster Cliff Brumby. He is famously killed by Jack Carter ([[Michael Caine]]) who beats him up and throws him from the roof of the [[Trinity Square Gateshead|Trinity Square]] [[multi-storey car park]] in [[Gateshead]], after discovering Brumby's involvement in his brother's death. He played alien dignitary Malpha and a props man on a film set in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' story \"[[The Daleks' Master Plan]]\" in 1965 and made two appearances in ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]''. Mosley also had a small role as the pub landlord in ''[[Queenie's Castle]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n==Fight arranger==\nHe was also a fencer and a stage and film fight arranger. He fenced with [[Terence Stamp]] in the film ''[[Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)|Far from the Madding Crowd]].'' He was a founder member of the Society of British Fight Directors and he arranged the ''Get Carter'' fight with Caine. Mosley was sometimes credited as '''Buddy Windrush'''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nBryan Mosley wed Norma Bowes in 1956; the couple had six children.<ref name=\"imdb\"/> Mosley was a practising [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] who had made at least one pilgrimage to [[Lourdes]].<ref name=\"bbc\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/318396.stm Bryan Mosley obituary], bbc.co.uk; accessed 28 September 2014.</ref> He was awarded an honorary degree from the [[University of Bradford]].\n\nMosley died on 9 February 1999 aged 67.His wife died on 16 October 2011, aged 79.<ref>{{cite web |title=Norma Mosley |url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/announcements/deaths/deaths/9310826.norma_mosley/ |website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus |accessdate=26 June 2019 |language=en |date=18 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1962|| ''[[A Kind of Loving (film)|A Kind of Loving]]'' || Bus Conductor || Uncredited\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[This Sporting Life]]'' || Man in bar || Uncredited\n|-\n|1963|| ''[[Billy Liar (film)|Billy Liar]]'' || Bit Part || Uncredited\n|-\n|1964|| ''[[Rattle of a Simple Man]]